# Git for dotfiles

I use two repositories: `.dotfiles/public` and `.dotfiles/private`. The first is for public display, the second is for my personal backups.

Firstly, I create the two directories for my repositories:
```
mkdir -p ~/.dotfiles/public
mkdir ~/.dotfiles/private
```

Then I create the following aliases: 
```
alias git_private_dotfiles="git --git-dir ~/.dotfiles/private/.git --work-tree=\$HOME"
alias git_public_dotfiles="git --git-dir ~/.dotfiles/public/.git --work-tree=\$HOME"
```

Then I init both repositories:
```
git_private_dotfiles init
git_public_dotfiles init
```

Then, for my public repository, I ignore everything by default:
```
echo "*" > ~/.dotfiles/public/.git/info/exclude
```

For my public repository, I can finally add the files and folder I wish to publish.

Then, for my private repository, I configure the files I want to ignore in a .gitignore:
```
vim ~/.dotfiles/private/.gitignore
git_private_dotfiles commit -m "Initial commit: gitignore"
```


